Data-Driven Decision-Making Benefits
  Using data helps gain valuable insights, verify assumptions, understand opportunities and challenges, and support planning.
  Examples include a dairy farmer choosing ice cream flavors based on customer surveys and an organization discovering employee perks preferences through structured feedback rather than gut feelings.

Five Essential Analytical Skills
  Curiosity and understanding context help analysts notice patterns and make predictions based on data.
  A technical mindset encourages moving beyond gut feelings to fact-based analysis and informed decisions.

Data Design and Strategy
  Data design involves organizing data logically to make it accessible and understandable for analysis.
  Data strategy encompasses the people, processes, and tools needed to solve problems and ensures alignment for successful data-driven decision-making.

Overall, these skills enable more confident, proactive, and efficient decision-making in business contexts.
